{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>Controllers</h1>
    <p>
        Controllers are the central traffic cops of your application. Their primary responsibility is to handle incoming requests,
        interact with the necessary models to retrieve data, and then pass that data to the appropriate view to be rendered.
        This keeps your application logic separate from your presentation logic.
    </p>
    <p>
        All controllers should be placed in the <code>app/Controllers</code> directory and should extend the <code>Rhapsody\Core\BaseController</code>.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>BaseController Features</h2>
    <p>
        The <code>BaseController</code> provides a rich set of helper methods and automatically injects core services
        so you can focus on your application logic. When you extend it, your controller automatically gains:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>A configured <strong>Twig environment</strong> with theme support and custom extensions.</li>
        <li>Access to the <strong>database</strong> via the <code>$this->db</code> property.</li>
        <li>Access to the <strong>cache</strong> via <code>$this->cache</code>.</li>
        <li>Built-in <strong>SEO helpers</strong> (Schema.org structured data).</li>
        <li>Twig extensions for <strong>React islands</strong>, <strong>named routes</strong>, and <strong>CSRF protection</strong>.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr>

    <h2>Creating a Controller</h2>
    <p>Here is a basic example of a controller class.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-php"><?php

namespace App\Controllers;

use Rhapsody\Core\BaseController;
use Rhapsody\Core\Request;
use Rhapsody\Core\Response;
use App\Models\User;

class PageController extends BaseController
{
    public function index(): Response
    {
        // The view() helper renders a Twig template
        return $this->view('home/index.twig', [
            'title' => 'Welcome',
        ]);
    }

    public function showUsers(Request $request): Response
    {
        $users = (new User())->findAll();
        
        return $this->view('home/users.twig', [
            'users' => $users,
        ]);
    }
}</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Returning Responses</h2>

    <h3>Returning a View</h3>
    <p>The <code>view()</code> helper renders a Twig template and returns a <code>Response</code> object with status 200.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">public function dashboard(): Response
{
    return $this->view('dashboard/index.twig', [
        'stats' => $this->getStats(),
    ], [
        'title'       => 'Dashboard',
        'description' => 'Your personal dashboard',
    ]);
}</code></pre>
    <p>
        The third parameter allows you to pass SEO metadata (<code>title</code>, <code>description</code>) that will be
        automatically merged into the view's <code>meta</code> variable.
    </p>

    <h3>Returning JSON</h3>
    <p>The <code>json()</code> helper creates a JSON response with the correct <code>Content-Type</code> header.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">public function getUser(string $id): Response
{
    $user = (new User())->findById($id);
    
    if (!$user) {
        return $this->json(['error' => 'User not found'], 404);
    }

    return $this->json($user);
}</code></pre>

    <h3>Returning a React Component</h3>
    <p>
        Rhapsody includes a first‑class integration with <strong>React</strong> via the <code>react()</code> method.
        This mounts a React component as a full‑page HTML response, with props serialised safely and Vite assets
        injected automatically.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">public function dashboard(): Response
{
    return $this->react('Dashboard', [
        'user'  => auth()->user()->toArray(),
        'stats' => $this->getDashboardStats(),
    ], [
        'title' => 'Dashboard',
    ]);
}</code></pre>
    <p>
        The <code>react()</code> method handles:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Serialising props as JSON (XSS‑safe).</li>
        <li>Injecting the CSRF token as a <code>&lt;meta&gt;</code> tag.</li>
        <li>Resolving Vite assets (development HMR or production manifest).</li>
        <li>Rendering a complete HTML document with the component mounted at <code>#rhapsody-root</code>.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        For more details, see the <a href="{{ base_url }}/docs/react">React Integration</a> documentation.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Accessing the Request</h2>
    <p>
        The router automatically injects an instance of the <code>Rhapsody\Core\Request</code> object as the first parameter
        to every controller action. This object provides a clean API for accessing request data.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">public function handleContact(Request $request): Response
{
    // Get the request method (e.g., 'post')
    $method = $request->getMethod();

    // Get all input (POST, JSON, PUT, etc.)
    $data = $request->getBody();

    // Get a specific query parameter from the URL
    $page = $request->getQueryParam('page', 1);

    // Get a specific POST value
    $email = $request->post('email');

    // Access uploaded files
    $files = $request->getFiles();
    
    // ...
}</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Generating URLs with Named Routes</h2>
    <p>
        The <code>BaseController</code> automatically registers the <code>RoutingExtension</code> with Twig,
        making the <code>route()</code> function available in all templates.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&lt;a href="&lcub;&lcub; route('profile.show', {id: user.id}) }}"&gt;View Profile&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
        In PHP (e.g., inside a controller), you can use <code>Router::generateUrl()</code>:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">use Rhapsody\Core\Routing\Router;

public function redirectToProfile(Request $request): Response
{
    $url = Router::generateUrl('profile.show', ['id' => $request->get('id')]);
    return redirect($url);
}</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Dependency Injection &amp; Lazy Loading</h2>
    <p>
        The container resolves your controllers and their dependencies automatically.
        If you type‑hint a service in your controller's constructor, it will be injected.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">namespace App\Controllers;

use App\Services\PaymentService;
use Rhapsody\Core\BaseController;

class CheckoutController extends BaseController
{
    public function __construct(
        private PaymentService $paymentService
    ) {}

    public function process(): Response
    {
        $this->paymentService->charge(...);
        // ...
    }
}</code></pre>
    <p>
        For performance, controllers are <strong>not lazy‑loaded</strong> (they are resolved eagerly).
        However, all other services injected into controllers <em>can</em> be lazy‑loaded if you enable
        the <code>LAZY_LOADING_ENABLED</code> setting in your <code>.env</code> file. This means that
        heavy services (like the ORM or mailer) are only instantiated when they are actually used.
    </p>
    <p>
        The <strong>Services</strong> panel in the debug toolbar shows which services were resolved
        and whether they were lazy‑loaded – perfect for performance tuning.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Debugging Controllers</h2>
    <p>
        The debug toolbar includes a <strong>Services</strong> panel that shows:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Which services were resolved during the request.</li>
        <li>How long each service took to instantiate.</li>
        <li>Whether the service was lazy‑loaded (green "Yes") or eager (red "No").</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        This is invaluable for identifying bottlenecks in your controller's dependency graph.
    </p>
    <p>
        The <strong>Middleware</strong> panel shows execution times for all middleware,
        helping you pinpoint slow components.
    </p>

    <hr>

